title: For Sale/Trade:  Fostech Echo II Trigger
postcontent: I have a Fostech Echo AR-II Trigger; it was installed and function checked; it has 20 rounds on it - works as advertised - below is the synopsis from the company.The Echo AR-II Trigger is a trigger for many but not all AR-15 platforms. The Echo AR-II trigger NO LONGER comes with a stripped carrier with gas key because it is no longer needed. You will use the M16 bolt carrier group already insdie your weapon. If you do not have a full auto carrier group in your weapon you will need to attain a full auto carrier in order for the Echo AR-II trigger to function. If you have any questions about the difference between a full auto carrier and a semi-automatic carrier please see our instruction manual that shows the illustration. You can also find this information at www.echoquestions.com. The Echo AR-II Trigger is a ground breaking drop in design that is approved by the ATF. The Echo AR-II Trigger allows the shooter to select from 3 different settings. Safe Mode: Firearm will not fire.Semi-Automatic Mode: Firearm fires when trigger is pulled.Echo Mode: Firearm fires when trigger is pulled and also when trigger is released.The Echo AR-II Trigger is designed with safety being the utmost priority. When the shooter is in the Echo Mode and depresses the trigger one round is fired, if the target moves, the shooter can move the selector to the safe position and a second round will not fire upon release.The Echo AR-II Trigger has several distinct features:PATENTED Design that gained ATF Approval (Patent # US 8,820,211 B1) Technology licensed through HIPERFIRE inside the Echo AR-II TriggerLight, clean, and crisp pull in Semi-Automatic ModeThe Echo AR-II Trigger is packed full of cutting edge technologyReliable function in Echo Mode

title: For Sale:  6 each Mossbergs - 22LR
postcontent: Selling 6 each Mossberg rifles, Model 144LSB.  These are 22 Long Rifles that were used in the very late 1960's and early to mid 1970's to teach shooting in a local Wichita, KS gun club.  My Dad was an NRA instructor at the time and procured these rifles to teach teenager level students about correct shooting positions, accuracy and especially gun safety.  The model 144LSB production started as early as 1967 and thus, I can find only one serial number on just one rifle.  It was not until the Federal Law in 1968 that serial numbers were required so, I am supposing these are 1967 era models.  These rifles have been stored for 40 years and are in generally good shape. They were cleaned about nine years ago and have not been fired for decades. Each of the bolt action rifles were numbered for storage and inventory when the shooting club was in operation.  Rifles, 2,3,4 and 6 have a front sight and an adjustible rear.  Rifle 1 and 5 are missing sights.  4 each of the rifles have sling mounts and a few have 5 round clips.  A rifle like these are obviously antiques and most are in good or better condition.  Remember, you had teenagers handling these rifles though, there were as carefull as could be safely expected.  Some of them could be worth a lot more than I am asking.
